WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:29.980 --> 00:00:31.940
﻿Plasma Youth Sports Games
with Unsuccess of the champion,

00:00:32.096 --> 00:00:34.607
would like to thank Slaven Bilić
for stepping in as the host.

00:00:34.860 --> 00:00:38.007
Bilić is one of the first sponsors,
ambassador and is our biggest promoter.

00:00:38.204 --> 00:00:41.412
He used his life and sports experience
in order to prepare high-quality content

00:00:41.725 --> 00:00:43.845
with his guests for all generations.
Thanks, Nane!

00:00:49.060 --> 00:00:53.020
Thank you on behalf
of all of us for taking the time.

00:00:53.660 --> 00:00:59.303
Many years have passed since you,
I don't want to say, left or abandoned us.

00:00:59.525 --> 00:01:01.420
Since you retired. -Yes.

00:01:02.620 --> 00:01:07.380
In a very simple way, without
fanfare and without pomp.

00:01:07.620 --> 00:01:13.580
On the other hand, there was something
mystical and inexplicable in all that.

00:01:13.980 --> 00:01:17.380
We all wondered, what happened?

00:01:17.780 --> 00:01:22.203
What are you doing now?
-Most of the time I’m a mom.

00:01:22.320 --> 00:01:24.727
You’re mostly a mom?
-Yes, that’s right.

00:01:24.921 --> 00:01:30.721
I thank God that I have the privilege
to devote my time to them.

00:01:31.940 --> 00:01:35.820
Since I’ve completed
a large part of my career.

00:01:36.060 --> 00:01:42.378
I occasionally do some projects,
but I’m not busy all day anymore.

00:01:42.714 --> 00:01:48.820
I don’t have to sit in an office,
and I have that freedom of movement.

00:01:49.700 --> 00:01:58.980
I believe that upbringing is very
important for children.

00:01:59.620 --> 00:02:02.274
They need their mother the most.

00:02:02.569 --> 00:02:05.790
Their upbringing is very important,
so I can afford to devote

00:02:05.950 --> 00:02:08.150
myself fully to them.

00:02:08.940 --> 00:02:12.660
Speaking of upbringing,
are you more...

00:02:14.180 --> 00:02:15.895
At least in theory, it’s said
that the father is a "gypsum"

00:02:16.045 --> 00:02:17.559
and the mother is the mom.

00:02:17.647 --> 00:02:19.504
How do you treat them,
like a "gypsum" or like a mom?

00:02:19.659 --> 00:02:21.259
I act more like a mom.

00:02:22.046 --> 00:02:26.840
I don’t know exactly what is
meant by the term "gypsum".

00:02:28.180 --> 00:02:32.300
However, as far as the role
of the father is concerned,

00:02:33.020 --> 00:02:36.813
it was decisive, at least for me.
-Yes. I read somewhere...

00:02:37.012 --> 00:02:41.462
I thought they called the father
"gypsum" because he is strict,

00:02:41.937 --> 00:02:44.742
referring to a conservative
upbringing, which is fine for me.

00:02:45.272 --> 00:02:48.112
However, that’s not true.

00:02:48.220 --> 00:02:50.326
They called him that
because of the fractures.

00:02:50.487 --> 00:02:55.260
Yes, even as a child growing up
when there was much more

00:02:55.682 --> 00:03:01.271
freedom than today, he climbed trees
a lot and was mischievous. -All right.

00:03:03.380 --> 00:03:06.340
Let’s reminisce a bit about the past.

00:03:06.573 --> 00:03:08.813
I don’t want to ask you
if you miss skiing,

00:03:08.967 --> 00:03:11.087
knowing that it’s been a long time.

00:03:11.311 --> 00:03:14.911
However, can you remember
the time when you retired.

00:03:15.089 --> 00:03:18.049
At least for the first
few years or months.

00:03:18.313 --> 00:03:21.960
Did you miss skiing or
did you ever regret it? -No.

00:03:22.150 --> 00:03:26.437
Did you feel emptiness
or relief? Or maybe both?

00:03:27.220 --> 00:03:31.700
I never thought...
-You just stopped? -Yes.

00:03:32.100 --> 00:03:36.180
That’s how you understood
that decision, but I didn’t.

00:03:36.900 --> 00:03:39.820
At the beginning of my last season,
I knew that I wouldn’t

00:03:40.020 --> 00:03:42.260
engage in skiing professionally again.

00:03:42.500 --> 00:03:45.860
I thought it was my personal
decision, not someone else’s.

00:03:46.100 --> 00:03:48.260
I’m a person who doesn’t like
to talk too much,

00:03:48.540 --> 00:03:51.060
especially not about
my own goals.

00:03:51.780 --> 00:03:54.780
I think then people
take a lot of energy from you.

00:03:56.225 --> 00:03:58.180
I wanted to do it my way.

00:03:58.420 --> 00:04:01.220
Because when someone knows what
will happen at the end of the season,

00:04:01.366 --> 00:04:03.246
then they ask you about it
in every interview:

00:04:03.495 --> 00:04:08.420
"This is one of your last races.
How will you deal with it?"

00:04:08.865 --> 00:04:10.459
I think it’s unnecessary.

00:04:10.669 --> 00:04:15.918
I just wanted to enjoy this ski season
as I enjoyed the previous ones.

00:04:17.097 --> 00:04:21.004
I set myself some goals that
I wanted to achieve that season.

00:04:21.500 --> 00:04:25.660
And I succeeded.
Thank God, and with a little luck.

00:04:26.589 --> 00:04:28.747
That’s how it happened,
and it happened suddenly.

00:04:28.949 --> 00:04:31.333
Only I knew about it.
Literally, no one but me.

00:04:31.457 --> 00:04:33.707
Nobody but you? -Not my brother,
not my dad, not my mom,

00:04:33.868 --> 00:04:36.308
not my coach, not anyone.
-It was sudden for us.

00:04:36.486 --> 00:04:41.486
Because there were two
things involved. First...

00:04:45.580 --> 00:04:49.900
That saying: "You should retire
at the peak of your fame."

00:04:50.140 --> 00:04:54.020
It sounds good in theory, but hardly
any athletes actually do it.

00:04:54.260 --> 00:04:56.300
They usually get "pushed away"
by the audience or the media, or...

00:04:56.469 --> 00:04:59.661
I mean in team sports -
you don’t get a contract.

00:04:59.827 --> 00:05:02.740
Rarely does one retire
at the peak, but you did.

00:05:02.981 --> 00:05:09.872
When you were at the peak
of your career, and still young.

00:05:10.818 --> 00:05:16.100
You were only 24. -Some people
are just starting at that age.

00:05:16.380 --> 00:05:21.380
That’s right. There was no reason,
and then suddenly, I stopped.

00:05:21.504 --> 00:05:23.824
Okay, but I don’t understand...

00:05:23.940 --> 00:05:26.331
That’s what you decided,
and then it’s okay.

00:05:26.495 --> 00:05:30.055
I’m not just talking about
the race adrenaline here,

00:05:30.420 --> 00:05:33.159
but also about the schedule.

00:05:33.497 --> 00:05:37.497
You were an athlete used
to constant obligations.

00:05:37.682 --> 00:05:40.565
Especially since it’s even more
demanding in individual sports

00:05:40.664 --> 00:05:42.384
than in team sports.

00:05:44.331 --> 00:05:50.112
It’s simply a sacrifice. -It’s not
a sacrifice, it’s an investment.

00:05:50.540 --> 00:05:56.020
Investment, yes. However,
you have to make big sacrifices.

00:05:56.311 --> 00:05:58.031
Especially in individual sports.

00:05:58.300 --> 00:06:01.980
In my opinion, it’s perspective,
I don’t see any sacrifice in that.

00:06:02.260 --> 00:06:06.380
I’m doing something I love
and I’m doing it well. -Right.

00:06:06.620 --> 00:06:10.460
When I stopped doing professional
sports, it was difficult for me.

00:06:10.700 --> 00:06:14.420
Tell me, who has the privilege
of doing what they love most?

00:06:14.620 --> 00:06:20.540
True. However, you can’t dismiss
what all athletes go through.

00:06:21.020 --> 00:06:25.340
There is a lot of sacrifice
in team sports.

00:06:25.540 --> 00:06:28.020
And even more in individual ones,
especially yours,

00:06:28.220 --> 00:06:31.515
the one we’re going to talk about.

00:06:32.157 --> 00:06:35.396
What she had to endure
to achieve those results.

00:06:35.785 --> 00:06:40.836
That’s commendable and admirable.
-It’s a matter of perspective.

00:06:41.007 --> 00:06:43.447
When it comes to me...

00:06:46.460 --> 00:06:50.180
I think I probably know
how to keep perspective.

00:06:50.980 --> 00:06:56.235
Maybe because I know myself well,
so it’s easier for me.

00:06:58.220 --> 00:07:01.626
I was never concerned with
what other people were doing.

00:07:02.134 --> 00:07:04.680
Or with external factors
I couldn’t influence.

00:07:04.798 --> 00:07:07.078
The only person I can influence is me.

00:07:08.300 --> 00:07:13.500
That’s why I liked to deal
with myself and my thoughts.

00:07:14.260 --> 00:07:16.348
And with how I could improve myself.

00:07:16.511 --> 00:07:20.035
I have never compared myself
to anyone else.

00:07:20.234 --> 00:07:22.418
And I never tried to copy
somebody else.

00:07:22.655 --> 00:07:26.775
It’s hard to do - and maybe
you have to be born that way.

00:07:26.946 --> 00:07:31.059
Or maybe work on yourself
to become like that.

00:07:31.298 --> 00:07:36.611
I was lucky to be able to think
calmly and without pressure,

00:07:37.220 --> 00:07:40.770
not burdening myself
with success or failure.

00:07:41.222 --> 00:07:43.653
You also have a brother...

00:07:45.260 --> 00:07:50.020
Athletes, when the time comes,
either stay in sport in some role

00:07:50.260 --> 00:07:55.780
or continue in veteran leagues.

00:07:59.740 --> 00:08:05.900
For example, Ivica - they start
doing thing with more adrenaline.

00:08:06.140 --> 00:08:10.460
And you just withdrew.
Are you aware...

00:08:10.940 --> 00:08:15.980
Just as you said,
you’re on the same side...

00:08:16.260 --> 00:08:22.900
In the opinion of many, you’re the best,
and in mine, without a doubt,

00:08:23.100 --> 00:08:26.260
an athlete from these areas.

00:08:26.620 --> 00:08:30.860
For your quality, career, medals -
we all know your success, charisma.

00:08:31.100 --> 00:08:34.780
But you achieved all that
in a special way.

00:08:34.980 --> 00:08:38.300
You were always simple, smiling.

00:08:38.540 --> 00:08:43.060
And doing that through a sport
that’s global, respected, and important.

00:08:43.380 --> 00:08:47.820
You’re both a champion
and a girl next door.

00:08:48.060 --> 00:08:57.740
Are you now, as a wife, mother, lady,
aware of what you have achieved?

00:09:00.140 --> 00:09:03.356
It’s silly to say I’m not aware of it.

00:09:07.900 --> 00:09:14.060
However, I think everything
was meant to happen that way.

00:09:14.340 --> 00:09:18.420
I don’t think I’m better
or more special than anyone else.

00:09:18.700 --> 00:09:25.594
We’re all people who chose to do
something, more or less successfully.

00:09:27.654 --> 00:09:30.675
To me, success doesn’t make a person.

00:09:31.771 --> 00:09:37.620
Whether it’s success in school,
work, sports, or anything else.

00:09:39.340 --> 00:09:47.225
Our daily attitude toward people and
community makes us who we are.

00:09:47.444 --> 00:09:52.374
And whether we’re more or less
successful, that’s fine or not.

00:09:52.663 --> 00:09:55.753
It’s good to be successful,
but it’s not what matters most.

00:09:55.940 --> 00:10:00.500
I don’t see anything extravagant
in what I’ve achieved.

00:10:00.740 --> 00:10:04.660
As strange as that sounds.

00:10:05.100 --> 00:10:07.860
I just enjoyed what I was doing.

00:10:08.100 --> 00:10:13.580
I was happy to see people
happy because of what I did.

00:10:14.180 --> 00:10:17.580
And that they went through
it all together with me.

00:10:20.340 --> 00:10:26.940
I don’t like exaggerations.
-Of course, because you’re complete.

00:10:27.220 --> 00:10:29.540
You’ve come full circle.

00:10:29.820 --> 00:10:38.980
At the same time, you’re charismatic,
confident, and motivated.

00:10:39.260 --> 00:10:41.940
You can say what you want,
but without those traits,

00:10:42.220 --> 00:10:45.340
you wouldn’t have achieved
those results.

00:10:45.580 --> 00:10:48.820
And on the other hand,
you’re modest,

00:10:49.060 --> 00:10:55.340
simple, and you treat
ordinary things normally.

00:10:55.620 --> 00:10:57.860
And that’s absolutely true.

00:10:58.100 --> 00:11:02.439
What we’re talking about
is not exaggeration, but fact.

00:11:02.614 --> 00:11:05.720
All right. -You achieved
that in a special way.

00:11:05.853 --> 00:11:08.142
But in the future,
someone else will do it.

00:11:08.314 --> 00:11:11.767
At that time, it was me
and I achieved success.

00:11:12.060 --> 00:11:16.100
Likewise, someone will
break those records one day.

00:11:16.591 --> 00:11:21.121
We’ll praise that person too.
We won’t overlook them.

00:11:24.713 --> 00:11:28.775
How did you fall
in love with skiing?

00:11:29.143 --> 00:11:31.977
We know your dad, Ante,
was an athlete and that he

00:11:32.210 --> 00:11:35.130
was involved in athletics,
handball, and skiing.

00:11:35.378 --> 00:11:37.884
I think he even played water polo.

00:11:38.179 --> 00:11:43.345
In one game in France,
he scored all the goals.

00:11:43.629 --> 00:11:45.429
That is, 24 of them.

00:11:45.777 --> 00:11:49.177
After he wasn’t invited
to the Yugoslav national team,

00:11:49.660 --> 00:11:54.980
he was disappointed and said
his children wouldn’t play team sports.

00:11:55.185 --> 00:11:59.171
Did you see yourself
in another sport at first,

00:11:59.318 --> 00:12:01.158
or was it just "poof",
straight into skiing?

00:12:01.460 --> 00:12:07.860
I was just an ordinary kid who
only did sports in primary school.

00:12:10.580 --> 00:12:15.580
My brother started skiing first...
I learned to ski when I was three,

00:12:15.820 --> 00:12:22.100
but I actually never liked it.
Mostly because I was always cold

00:12:22.300 --> 00:12:25.380
and because there was
so much equipment.

00:12:25.780 --> 00:12:31.020
Later in my career that followed me,
having to carry around all that gear.

00:12:31.900 --> 00:12:35.540
But honestly, in the beginning,
I didn’t like skiing.

00:12:36.380 --> 00:12:40.020
When we went on family ski trips,
I would always find ways

00:12:40.300 --> 00:12:44.900
to avoid skiing that day, like saying
I’d rather go sledding instead.

00:12:45.140 --> 00:12:49.540
My brother was in a ski club
in Zagreb, and later,

00:12:49.740 --> 00:12:53.500
since my dad was a handball coach
in Slovenia, in Celje,

00:12:54.220 --> 00:12:58.740
we spent a year there and my brother
joined the local ski club.

00:12:59.020 --> 00:13:02.980
But I still didn’t do any sports,
except P. E. at school.

00:13:03.260 --> 00:13:06.180
When we moved back to Zagreb,
I was in the third grade,

00:13:06.460 --> 00:13:11.180
I started playing handball.
Both my parents played handball,

00:13:11.460 --> 00:13:16.260
so I guess it just made sense.
They said I was doing okay,

00:13:16.940 --> 00:13:22.500
that I had a good sense for it,
but there were some things

00:13:22.740 --> 00:13:28.620
about team sports that didn’t
make sense to me at all.

00:13:29.580 --> 00:13:32.939
For example, you’ll know this from
football, the coach says:

00:13:33.139 --> 00:13:36.099
we’re running this play,
let’s call it "XY", right?

00:13:37.580 --> 00:13:44.620
And we start playing that play, but
at one point I see the goal is open,

00:13:44.860 --> 00:13:48.780
I can shoot, so I stop the play
and shoot - and score!

00:13:49.820 --> 00:13:54.100
And then the coach starts yelling
at me for not finishing the play.

00:13:54.300 --> 00:13:58.020
And I ask, "Wait, is the goal here to
finish the play or to score a goal?"

00:13:58.220 --> 00:14:01.380
I mean, it was just practice,

00:14:01.580 --> 00:14:05.140
but we were apparently training
to run the play exactly as planned.

00:14:05.420 --> 00:14:08.860
Or, for example, the goalkeeper would
say, "Don’t shoot that hard,"

00:14:09.140 --> 00:14:12.639
or something like that... and there
was always some referee issue.

00:14:12.796 --> 00:14:17.356
I could never deal with referees,
honestly. I don't know how you do it.

00:14:18.766 --> 00:14:21.295
Like, you can't even
explain it to them.

00:14:21.514 --> 00:14:24.615
No matter how much you try to,
it's still in vain.

00:14:24.901 --> 00:14:27.764
It just didn't seem fair to me.

00:14:28.387 --> 00:14:31.584
I actually started skiing
because my brother went to

00:14:31.790 --> 00:14:35.230
summer conditioning training to
Bjelolasica with his ski club.

00:14:36.420 --> 00:14:40.380
It was summer break, I didn’t have
anything better to do,

00:14:40.620 --> 00:14:47.325
so I just went with them. I met the
ski team there, we became friends,

00:14:47.607 --> 00:14:53.413
we were fooling around, pushing each
other to jump into the cold pool,

00:14:53.740 --> 00:14:58.300
I even split my chin open. They were
all great kids, we got along well.

00:14:58.500 --> 00:15:01.220
Then school started, autumn came,
I went back to school,

00:15:01.420 --> 00:15:06.140
and Ivica went on his first ski trip
to Kaprun, in Austria, with the club.

00:15:06.271 --> 00:15:08.229
And the people there were like,
"Where’s Freckles?",

00:15:08.341 --> 00:15:10.562
I had a lot of freckles back then,
so that was my nickname,

00:15:10.704 --> 00:15:13.479
"Where’s Freckles, where’s Freckles?"
So I said, fine, I’ll go.

00:15:13.753 --> 00:15:16.221
I honestly didn’t have
a clue about skiing.

00:15:16.379 --> 00:15:20.125
They put me in a group with all the
kids who already skied normally,

00:15:20.476 --> 00:15:22.992
and I just kept falling and falling.

00:15:23.627 --> 00:15:27.062
My dad got involved in skiing at that
time too, he worked with Ivica,

00:15:27.171 --> 00:15:29.453
and he wasn't that serious with me.

00:15:29.778 --> 00:15:32.664
He said it was better for me
to focus on school and handball.

00:15:32.836 --> 00:15:34.835
There was even talk that
I might start playing tennis,

00:15:34.959 --> 00:15:36.750
but that never really happened.

00:15:38.396 --> 00:15:42.123
How old were you then?
-I was ten years old.

00:15:44.180 --> 00:15:47.780
And then one coach, Ivo Drinjković,
he was the president of the club,

00:15:48.020 --> 00:15:53.460
Dr. Ivo Drinjković, he said, "Come on,
kid, you come skiing with me,

00:15:53.660 --> 00:15:56.380
forget about them,
let them do their thing..."

00:15:56.580 --> 00:15:58.860
And somehow I picked
everything up really quickly,

00:15:59.060 --> 00:16:02.700
and literally after a month
I was already going to competitions

00:16:02.900 --> 00:16:06.140
with the rest of them.
Apparently, it came naturally to me

00:16:06.304 --> 00:16:08.304
and that’s how it all started.

00:16:08.497 --> 00:16:12.657
In every sport, parents sacrifice
a lot, give things up for their child...

00:16:12.805 --> 00:16:16.100
Of course, that’s natural.
-Out of love, obviously. -Naturally.

00:16:16.380 --> 00:16:19.980
Some do it more, some less, and
unfortunately not everyone succeeds.

00:16:20.220 --> 00:16:25.060
Sometimes it just stops,
maybe the child loses motivation

00:16:25.260 --> 00:16:29.740
or whatever, doesn’t matter. But we
know the ones who did make it, right,

00:16:29.940 --> 00:16:32.167
and they’re the ones
people talk about.

00:16:32.370 --> 00:16:36.631
Talking with Ivanišević, for example,
or with Đoković, both of whom were

00:16:36.820 --> 00:16:41.220
guests on this show, I noticed that
your path and your development

00:16:42.380 --> 00:16:45.826
are almost a copy-paste of theirs.

00:16:46.058 --> 00:16:49.498
Because in all three cases, yours,
theirs, and Blanka Vlašić’s,

00:16:50.020 --> 00:16:53.300
it’s about an individual sport
where the family...

00:16:53.540 --> 00:16:56.980
Without the family’s support,
especially in systems and countries

00:16:57.173 --> 00:17:00.133
like ours, or in this whole region
where things are not organized

00:17:00.334 --> 00:17:02.694
or guaranteed, it’s impossible.

00:17:02.848 --> 00:17:05.629
It’s almost identical,
with one big difference:

00:17:06.181 --> 00:17:09.421
for them, tennis courts
or athletic tracks are something

00:17:09.723 --> 00:17:12.520
they can walk or take the bus to.

00:17:12.880 --> 00:17:17.680
But in your case, there’s no snow,
no conditions, nothing.

00:17:18.060 --> 00:17:21.580
So was that a crazy idea of one man,

00:17:21.780 --> 00:17:25.300
your father, who wanted
to prove to everyone:

00:17:25.500 --> 00:17:29.500
"I’ll take the hardest sport there is
and show that it can be done."

00:17:29.700 --> 00:17:32.940
It’s like that movie Cool Runnings...
-Cool Runnings, yes, exactly...

00:17:33.140 --> 00:17:36.540
Except that was a film...
-And this was real life.

00:17:36.740 --> 00:17:42.020
Yes, I know my dad competed for the
Yugoslav national team in skiing,

00:17:42.700 --> 00:17:45.380
and I know he really, really loved it.

00:17:45.580 --> 00:17:48.740
He used to tell all these stories
about going skiing with his friends,

00:17:48.940 --> 00:17:51.100
how they’d take the train
to Kranjska Gora,

00:17:51.300 --> 00:17:53.700
and that part of the country
was always full of snow.

00:17:53.940 --> 00:17:56.820
All those adventures, everything
they had to go through just to get to

00:17:57.020 --> 00:18:02.940
the slopes and actually ski,
I found that fascinating to listen to.

00:18:03.300 --> 00:18:07.580
It was incredibly fun to hear
how much passion they had for it.

00:18:07.820 --> 00:18:11.057
So in a way, I think that passion
of his just carried over.

00:18:11.211 --> 00:18:14.823
Handball is a team sport,
that didn’t really stick,

00:18:14.960 --> 00:18:17.768
then I think he also played some
water polo, and so on.

00:18:17.891 --> 00:18:20.290
Back then people played
multiple sports.

00:18:20.443 --> 00:18:23.870
It wasn’t like today, where
everything is strictly one thing.

00:18:24.392 --> 00:18:29.511
You can’t really say it was less
serious, but now, with technology

00:18:29.664 --> 00:18:32.024
and everything else,
the level of performance required

00:18:32.380 --> 00:18:37.784
doesn’t even let you have a normal
life, let alone practice more sports.

00:18:43.279 --> 00:18:45.971
So now, as a parent,

00:18:47.090 --> 00:18:52.772
I don’t think I could have that same
strength or vision that he had.

00:18:53.667 --> 00:18:57.003
Of course, everyone asks,
"Will your kids be skiers too?"

00:18:57.165 --> 00:18:59.287
But come on,
let the kids just be kids.

00:18:59.499 --> 00:19:02.339
Let them grow and develop
at their own pace.

00:19:02.484 --> 00:19:04.364
That’s probably a topic in itself,

00:19:04.503 --> 00:19:07.459
how people expect that
if someone was successful in sports,

00:19:07.648 --> 00:19:11.368
then their children automatically have
to be Olympic or world champions too.

00:19:11.474 --> 00:19:13.435
It usually doesn’t work that way.
-Well, I mean...

00:19:13.612 --> 00:19:15.850
It doesn’t really matter
whether it does or not,

00:19:15.996 --> 00:19:20.420
but if everyone keeps pushing that
idea... To go back to my dad...

00:19:22.490 --> 00:19:26.787
I honestly don’t know what kind of
vision or strength he had in his mind.

00:19:27.007 --> 00:19:31.807
He had my mom, his wife, and without
her, it would’ve been zero points.

00:19:31.984 --> 00:19:35.608
All credit to him for everything, but
without mom... -Of course, of course.

00:19:35.780 --> 00:19:38.881
Nothing without mom... -But tell me,
how did you actually got hooked?

00:19:39.056 --> 00:19:43.413
Usually, when kids go into sports,
whether a team or individual sport,

00:19:44.171 --> 00:19:49.390
they have idols. You know,
local or national heroes:

00:19:49.802 --> 00:19:53.362
some want to be the next
Modrić, Boban, Bokšić, Džeko,

00:19:53.749 --> 00:19:56.949
Dražen Petrović, Kukoč,
Divac, or Janica.

00:19:58.620 --> 00:20:01.620
But with you - you didn’t...

00:20:01.820 --> 00:20:05.140
And usually, you dream about it with
your friends, your neighborhood crew,

00:20:05.340 --> 00:20:08.420
but was it even possible
to dream a dream that big,

00:20:08.620 --> 00:20:12.020
the one you ended up living?
I mean, there’s no snow here...

00:20:14.260 --> 00:20:19.486
Well, honestly, I never really
thought of my sport,

00:20:19.668 --> 00:20:22.877
and this might sound silly,
I never took it seriously.

00:20:23.690 --> 00:20:25.723
You couldn’t have taken it
more seriously than you did!

00:20:25.846 --> 00:20:28.575
No, really, to me it was just play,
fun...

00:20:30.457 --> 00:20:32.879
Everything was play,
fun, and adventure.

00:20:34.260 --> 00:20:40.980
Right. So Ante was basically
Spielberg, and your mom too...

00:20:41.620 --> 00:20:46.140
They once asked me, "At what point
did you know you wanted to ski?"

00:20:47.260 --> 00:20:53.900
I never really thought about it,
it just kind of evolved naturally.

00:20:54.100 --> 00:20:57.740
I enjoyed it because of
the kids in the club.

00:20:57.980 --> 00:21:00.220
I liked spending time with them.

00:21:00.500 --> 00:21:05.048
That’s why I skied, for the company,
the fun, the friends.

00:21:05.334 --> 00:21:09.970
I mean, I guess... I look at my son
now and he’s more interested in

00:21:10.220 --> 00:21:14.900
playing and hanging out with friends
than in being good at something.

00:21:15.940 --> 00:21:19.300
Right. -And it just went
naturally from there.

00:21:19.580 --> 00:21:23.460
I was lucky that I was good at it. I
went to those children’s competitions.

00:21:23.660 --> 00:21:28.820
Imagine being 12 years old and going
to Italy, France, meeting new people,

00:21:29.020 --> 00:21:34.580
kids from America, Canada, Japan...
For me, that was all wow.

00:21:35.380 --> 00:21:37.980
That was the fun part,
everything else was secondary.

00:21:38.220 --> 00:21:44.662
I get that, but still... -And then that
thing slowly became more serious.

00:21:44.900 --> 00:21:47.865
When I moved into adult skiing, for
us, that’s when you start FIS races,

00:21:48.115 --> 00:21:51.075
I was 16 when when I started that...

00:21:52.506 --> 00:21:55.586
And suddenly you realize,
"Okay, this is serious."

00:21:55.818 --> 00:21:57.765
I’d look around and see everyone
so serious, so I thought,

00:21:57.870 --> 00:21:59.833
"I guess I have to be serious too."

00:21:59.942 --> 00:22:02.305
But then I’d ask myself:
"Why should I?"

00:22:02.683 --> 00:22:06.516
Somehow, for me,
it alwas like a game.

00:22:06.735 --> 00:22:12.180
I enjoyed every day, whatever
we were doing, training or otherwise,

00:22:12.540 --> 00:22:18.204
I just kept trying to challenge
myself through it all.

00:22:18.683 --> 00:22:21.843
I get it, and that’s what
I wanted to ask you.

00:22:22.580 --> 00:22:27.940
Even though it’s not
often portrayed that way.

00:22:28.340 --> 00:22:33.340
You once said you never felt like you
didn’t have money. -Yes. -Right? -Yes.

00:22:33.620 --> 00:22:38.500
But on the other hand, when we watch
the film or read about it, it’s clear,

00:22:41.459 --> 00:22:48.100
you were out there camping,
living almost like Robinson Crusoe.

00:22:48.420 --> 00:22:52.020
You’d be on Mljet, and okay,
that’s fine because it’s summer,

00:22:52.260 --> 00:22:56.700
but then winter comes, and it’s a
Russian Lada, 12 years old...

00:22:56.900 --> 00:22:59.140
The legend - that Russian Lada...

00:22:59.380 --> 00:23:04.485
Right? You drive to Austria,
you sleep... It wasn’t ideal.

00:23:04.706 --> 00:23:06.626
No, it wasn’t ideal.
-You didn’t stay in hotels.

00:23:06.882 --> 00:23:09.762
And since skiing is a morning sport
anyway, you’d go early,

00:23:10.105 --> 00:23:13.454
before anyone else was there, so that
no one would see you on the slopes,

00:23:13.603 --> 00:23:15.603
because you’d have to pay
them otherwise.

00:23:15.827 --> 00:23:19.774
These are the kinds of things that,
for a child, might seem okay,

00:23:19.950 --> 00:23:23.110
but in reality, they’re tough.
-Not really, because as a child,

00:23:23.287 --> 00:23:26.927
you don’t have that perception
of how the world is supposed to work.

00:23:27.119 --> 00:23:29.165
You only know what you know.

00:23:29.377 --> 00:23:32.470
I mean, I was aware that when
we went to children’s races like

00:23:32.720 --> 00:23:36.071
Topolino or Pinocchio,
we’d stay in hotels.

00:23:36.328 --> 00:23:38.768
But then, say,
when we’d go to Austria,

00:23:39.031 --> 00:23:42.031
my dad would have enough money
for the ski pass, but not for a hotel.

00:23:42.193 --> 00:23:45.313
I’d sleep in the car, and the two of
them would sleep outside somewhere,

00:23:45.497 --> 00:23:49.417
or make some kind of... I mean, we
didn’t sleep in tents, not exactly,

00:23:49.657 --> 00:23:54.297
but they’d make a small bivouac,
hide somewhere, and that’s how it was.

00:23:54.568 --> 00:23:58.848
To me, it was all kind of cool.
I found it fun.

00:23:59.420 --> 00:24:02.900
That's absolutely understandable.
-And I enjoyed it.

00:24:03.062 --> 00:24:08.824
Your brother's here, Ante and mom.
You're all in this, all all-in.

00:24:09.058 --> 00:24:13.590
You're all holding one pole, and
you all want the same outcome.

00:24:13.811 --> 00:24:18.144
Ivanišević has a sister
with her own needs,

00:24:18.820 --> 00:24:23.100
Đoković has two brothers, Ančić has...
-Everyone's got something.

00:24:23.340 --> 00:24:25.972
There's a bit of everything.
And you're all...

00:24:26.248 --> 00:24:30.808
I understand your role.
And Ivica’s and Ante's, of course.

00:24:31.173 --> 00:24:34.580
What did mom do?
-Mom did everything.

00:24:35.300 --> 00:24:39.580
Everything moms do.
Dad was the coach, of course.

00:24:39.820 --> 00:24:46.614
You drive 12 hours to France by car.
Prepares skis - he handled the "guy stuff".

00:24:47.003 --> 00:24:49.371
Mom did everything else.
Copying school materials.

00:24:49.552 --> 00:24:53.580
Back then, you couldn't just
see what was done online.

00:24:53.820 --> 00:24:56.420
You take a notebook and write.

00:24:58.140 --> 00:25:00.780
She travelled with us.

00:25:00.980 --> 00:25:08.060
When we got a bit better financially,
we stayed in apartments.

00:25:08.260 --> 00:25:12.540
We didn't sleep in hotels,
and she would cook for us.

00:25:13.220 --> 00:25:15.820
She was there with us,
taking care of everything.

00:25:16.260 --> 00:25:21.500
Basically, logistics. Without her,
things just wouldn't work.

00:25:22.300 --> 00:25:26.900
When did you attend school regularly?
-Until high school. -Until high school.

00:25:27.540 --> 00:25:30.820
Until high school, then I did
correspondence school. -Yes, yes.

00:25:31.300 --> 00:25:37.620
Unfortunately, here you can't really...
Especially not with skiing.

00:25:37.860 --> 00:25:40.540
If you play basketball, handball,
or some other sport,

00:25:40.740 --> 00:25:44.900
you go to the gym and come back.
-You're home. -Maybe on weekends.

00:25:45.140 --> 00:25:49.460
But skiing... I'd be gone a week,
a whole month sometimes.

00:25:50.180 --> 00:25:52.540
So that's a bit tricky.

00:25:54.460 --> 00:25:56.671
It's a shame we don't
have something like...

00:25:56.821 --> 00:25:58.710
That's called the American system.

00:25:58.874 --> 00:26:02.265
You can do both at the same time.
One doesn't work without the other.

00:26:02.501 --> 00:26:07.621
If you're not good in sports, you can't
really function normally... I mean, you can,

00:26:07.909 --> 00:26:11.429
in school, but it helps a lot
if you're good in sports.

00:26:11.621 --> 00:26:14.340
If you're bad in school,
they even cut your sports.

00:26:14.501 --> 00:26:17.501
They tried that in our
sports high schools.

00:26:17.654 --> 00:26:21.734
There's still a sports high school.
-It's a bit rigid. -Not the same system.

00:26:22.020 --> 00:26:27.220
Still rigid. -You can go to
tournaments, but mostly be in school.

00:26:27.405 --> 00:26:29.605
But okay, that’s how it is.

00:26:29.789 --> 00:26:31.549
Tell me...

00:26:33.540 --> 00:26:35.740
That's mother Marica.

00:26:36.740 --> 00:26:43.265
About Ante... We know about dad, of course,
but his methods were sometimes called

00:26:44.660 --> 00:26:50.540
extreme, harsh, even inhuman.

00:26:50.900 --> 00:26:54.380
They criticized him - how can you
do that to your kids?

00:26:54.580 --> 00:26:58.217
Quite the opposite. You can only do that
to your own kids, because you want the best.

00:26:58.508 --> 00:27:02.193
Only with them can you do it.
How do you remember that?

00:27:02.495 --> 00:27:06.855
Those Spartan trainings. Again,
copy-paste from Joško Vlašić,

00:27:07.220 --> 00:27:11.620
from Ivanišević's father.
So that's kind of the standard here.

00:27:11.820 --> 00:27:18.460
Ante’s sessions were,
somehow, brutally hard.

00:27:19.780 --> 00:27:22.340
Again, it’s a matter of perspective.

00:27:22.780 --> 00:27:28.700
I don’t think that, watching others
train, I would’ve quit skiing

00:27:29.323 --> 00:27:34.555
even if I had to train that way.
It’s monotonous and boring,

00:27:34.740 --> 00:27:42.300
and every day the same. Literally.
Every training with dad was fun.

00:27:43.540 --> 00:27:49.020
It was never the same.
I was never bored training.

00:27:49.260 --> 00:27:53.060
We always trained outdoors,
which I loved. Gymnastics and

00:27:53.260 --> 00:27:57.215
similar stuff we did later,
at the Faculty of Kinesiology.

00:27:58.020 --> 00:28:02.500
But outside, where
every step is different.

00:28:02.740 --> 00:28:06.500
If I had to go to the gym
and lift weights all the time,

00:28:06.740 --> 00:28:14.900
same movement, same environment,
stuffy space - not fun at all.

00:28:15.180 --> 00:28:18.220
Boring to the limits.
-To you it was an adventure.

00:28:18.460 --> 00:28:23.940
I was having fun. Even now
I love jumping from high cliffs.

00:28:24.140 --> 00:28:28.420
I love it. Some find it
extreme. To me,

00:28:28.620 --> 00:28:31.780
it’s extreme to sit eight hours
in an office.

00:28:31.980 --> 00:28:34.700
Early mornings? -Sorry?
-Getting up early?

00:28:34.900 --> 00:28:39.100
Now it’s a problem.
Back then it wasn’t.

00:28:39.460 --> 00:28:42.620
Because I went to bed
on time, you know.

00:28:43.660 --> 00:28:52.624
So... my character isn’t
the easiest to work with

00:28:55.271 --> 00:29:01.876
for coaches, I have my own
views and visions.

00:29:04.033 --> 00:29:07.900
I know myself - what I can do
and how. Some things I see

00:29:08.380 --> 00:29:12.540
just wouldn’t suit me,
so I don’t want to do them.

00:29:12.780 --> 00:29:17.699
That’s hard when you have a coach,
unless it’s your dad and coach.

00:29:18.176 --> 00:29:23.496
He’s still my dad, he won’t send me...
-And you trust him, of course. -Yes.

00:29:23.980 --> 00:29:30.940
He can handle all my quirks.
A strict coach would send you home,

00:29:31.140 --> 00:29:35.860
you’d get punished, or whatever.
I was never punished. Never.

00:29:38.100 --> 00:29:45.300
That’s what was cool with dad.
He’d say: do ten sit-ups.

00:29:45.940 --> 00:29:51.860
Whatever. He never counted
what or how you did it.

00:29:52.140 --> 00:29:56.100
He’d think, correct you sometimes.
He always let us draw

00:29:56.340 --> 00:30:01.370
our own conclusions,
then he’d explain.

00:30:01.669 --> 00:30:06.860
Janičko, that’s what he calls me.
"Look, if I tell you to do ten of something,

00:30:07.100 --> 00:30:11.540
whether you do nine or twelve,
that’s up to you.

00:30:12.140 --> 00:30:16.500
You’re doing it for yourself,
not for me.

00:30:16.780 --> 00:30:21.140
If you do nine, you’re cheating
yourself, not me."

00:30:21.926 --> 00:30:25.886
Responsibility, yes. -You must
learn responsibility for that.

00:30:26.260 --> 00:30:32.820
Sometimes I did nine, I admit.
What was great with him -

00:30:34.940 --> 00:30:45.060
trainings were specific.
Hard, but fun. Except in summer,

00:30:45.380 --> 00:30:50.412
when it was unbearably hot.
That’s when training was worst,

00:30:51.342 --> 00:30:56.108
but that’s the climate.
-You said you did nine.

00:30:56.291 --> 00:31:01.155
Sorry to interrupt. Did you ever
do twelve? Or not your type? -What?

00:31:01.375 --> 00:31:06.069
Sit-ups. -No, I didn’t. -You said
you did nine... -Ivica’s that type.

00:31:06.420 --> 00:31:12.300
My brother is, I’m not. Rarely.
-It pushes you subconsciously.

00:31:12.540 --> 00:31:21.984
Rarely. Since I was a kid,
I’ve always thought about

00:31:22.975 --> 00:31:28.343
when I perform an exercise,
how much strength I need,

00:31:28.624 --> 00:31:36.814
how to do it well, fast, right,
and save energy. Efficiency -

00:31:37.384 --> 00:31:43.955
that was my main goal.
To make my movement efficient.

00:31:44.170 --> 00:31:50.595
At the highest level,
but never wasting energy.

00:31:51.900 --> 00:31:56.300
There might come a moment
when you’ll need that energy.

00:31:56.500 --> 00:32:01.500
If you waste it before that,
neither your mind nor body works.

00:32:01.775 --> 00:32:03.775
That’s the Dalmatian in you.

00:32:04.185 --> 00:32:06.079
Exactly as much as needed.

00:32:06.522 --> 00:32:08.322
Maybe a bit...

00:32:09.860 --> 00:32:14.940
You’ve mentioned him a few times -
the thing that sets you apart.

00:32:16.220 --> 00:32:19.740
That’s Ivica, your older brother.

00:32:20.500 --> 00:32:25.420
He said you pushed each other,
helped each other.

00:32:25.740 --> 00:32:33.125
It was simply a shared success.
Your success was his, and his yours.

00:32:34.100 --> 00:32:39.700
Was there any jealousy -
not negative, but competitive?

00:32:39.980 --> 00:32:43.740
To be better than him and all that?
-Of course.

00:32:44.020 --> 00:32:47.820
I was really lucky
that he’s older than me

00:32:48.060 --> 00:32:50.700
and that we do the same sport.

00:32:50.940 --> 00:32:58.500
For much of my childhood,
skiing in kids’ categories,

00:32:59.420 --> 00:33:04.304
since he started earlier
in adult FIS competitions,

00:33:05.780 --> 00:33:10.300
I was always with him,
and he was always with men.

00:33:10.580 --> 00:33:13.900
He trained with them, too.
So I had the privilege

00:33:14.180 --> 00:33:18.660
to train with them as well,
to compare myself to them.

00:33:22.180 --> 00:33:27.860
He was like my pacer. -Yeah, yeah.
-Like in athletics, someone ahead of you.

00:33:28.140 --> 00:33:32.940
That worked for him too. Whenever
I started catching up to him,

00:33:33.180 --> 00:33:36.540
when he saw it got serious,
he’d tighten up.

00:33:36.845 --> 00:33:39.063
"No way a girl passes me."

00:33:39.715 --> 00:33:45.675
It was funny. But definitely
we were a "push and pull" team.

00:33:46.260 --> 00:33:50.740
It was great for me because...
I was for a long time a forerunner -

00:33:51.260 --> 00:33:56.197
the one who skis before racers.
There are three who clear the track,

00:33:56.350 --> 00:33:59.408
check that everything’s fine,
and all that.

00:34:00.660 --> 00:34:03.700
I think that period gave me a lot.

00:34:03.940 --> 00:34:05.980
When he moved into more
serious skiing,

00:34:06.165 --> 00:34:10.005
I was still in junior categories.
Always with him,

00:34:10.340 --> 00:34:17.484
always watching the guys ski.
I tried to get as close to them as I could.

00:34:17.700 --> 00:34:21.234
Not fully possible,
but within limits, yes.

00:34:22.340 --> 00:34:26.620
That was a really good
period for me.

00:34:26.980 --> 00:34:31.940
For him, less so -
having me as a sister

00:34:32.180 --> 00:34:35.100
and being together
was more for me than for him.

00:34:35.500 --> 00:34:41.235
Maybe I misunderstood -
correct me if I’m wrong.

00:34:41.633 --> 00:34:48.805
When both you and he competed,
you were much more successful.

00:34:49.420 --> 00:34:52.219
You even once said
one reason you retired

00:34:52.492 --> 00:34:57.516
was so your father could focus
entirely on him,

00:34:57.758 --> 00:35:00.780
since your dad traveled with you.
-Exactly. -Right?

00:35:01.041 --> 00:35:05.321
That’s how it ended up.
When you retired,

00:35:05.709 --> 00:35:09.829
he exploded. Was that because
your dad, as the authority,

00:35:10.100 --> 00:35:14.900
was now with him -
and also the pressure he felt

00:35:15.100 --> 00:35:19.620
from the nation’s expectations?
Like, "Your sister wins everything,

00:35:19.820 --> 00:35:24.140
now it’s your turn."
That’s heavy to carry.

00:35:27.300 --> 00:35:31.860
I’ve built a theory
that he pushed you a bit,

00:35:32.140 --> 00:35:35.660
and you held him back a bit.
Even with the same training,

00:35:35.723 --> 00:35:40.243
you can’t get the same results
in men’s and women’s skiing.

00:35:40.356 --> 00:35:42.272
Because you’re not the same person.

00:35:42.436 --> 00:35:46.273
In character, he and I
are very different. -How?

00:35:47.700 --> 00:35:53.020
He’s a devoted missionary type.
He sees only skiing.

00:35:53.380 --> 00:35:56.580
Sure, he plays guitar,
has many interests.

00:35:56.780 --> 00:36:04.846
But his focus is extremely...
In my view, overloaded

00:36:05.960 --> 00:36:08.768
with things he can’t control.

00:36:11.060 --> 00:36:13.660
﻿And a lot of things really get to him.

00:36:13.980 --> 00:36:17.180
I think that when you
focus too much on something,

00:36:17.980 --> 00:36:21.500
you actually end up
holding yourself back.

00:36:22.420 --> 00:36:26.665
I was always much more relaxed about it.
For me, it was more like,

00:36:26.849 --> 00:36:29.344
"Great, the Olympics are coming up!"

00:36:29.524 --> 00:36:34.596
It is great, and I’m happy about it,
but at the end of the day, it’s just a race.

00:36:34.824 --> 00:36:37.624
If not these Olympics,  then there’ll
be new ones in four years.

00:36:37.837 --> 00:36:41.517
Sure, it’s a long wait, but that’s life.
There are worse things. Much worse.

00:36:41.760 --> 00:36:48.299
You get in a car, crash, and that’s it.
So, all of this is just part of life.

00:36:48.580 --> 00:36:51.220
Everything, really everything,
can be simple.

00:36:51.420 --> 00:36:55.020
It doesn’t matter
what others say or think.

00:36:55.260 --> 00:36:59.612
Once, I finished a race in eighth place,
and I was over the moon.

00:37:00.708 --> 00:37:06.737
I mean, completely happy,
like I’d just won an Olympic gold medal.

00:37:07.431 --> 00:37:11.751
Because I’d been through a tough period.
I was coming back from an injury,

00:37:12.410 --> 00:37:15.770
and things just weren’t going well.
One race went kind of okay.

00:37:16.058 --> 00:37:18.018
It was a giant slalom...

00:37:18.404 --> 00:37:22.484
And I thought, "Great, I did it after all.
There’s still something I need to fix..."

00:37:22.931 --> 00:37:25.565
In that moment, I was really happy.

00:37:25.909 --> 00:37:28.949
I could see that I’d reached
a certain level of consistency,

00:37:29.338 --> 00:37:33.258
that I had stability, so from there,
I could start building and improving,

00:37:33.700 --> 00:37:38.900
slowly and steadily. But then, when I talked
to my dad and the other coaches,

00:37:39.404 --> 00:37:45.087
they said it was a disaster. And I thought,
"Come on, people, I finished eighth!

00:37:45.227 --> 00:37:48.758
I haven’t been eighth in a long time..."
Be happy for me, because I’m happy.

00:37:48.885 --> 00:37:51.078
I’m satisfied. And that has
to count for something.

00:37:51.257 --> 00:37:53.897
It means I still have motivation.
I didn’t want to hear things like,

00:37:54.160 --> 00:37:58.415
"You didn’t do this right, you didn’t do that,
why this, why that?"

00:37:59.204 --> 00:38:06.164
I thought, "Just let me be happy with
finishing eighth, even if it’s not perfect."

00:38:06.419 --> 00:38:09.219
But at that moment,
that was the best I could do.

00:38:09.395 --> 00:38:12.195
That doesn’t mean...
Things got better later on.

00:38:12.559 --> 00:38:16.159
But people can really kill your motivation
with some of those unnecessary comments.

00:38:16.407 --> 00:38:19.367
And if you can’t, yourself,
see how much you’re worth,

00:38:19.608 --> 00:38:21.968
how capable you are,
then it just  sweeps you away,

00:38:22.309 --> 00:38:28.869
like a flood, and you sink. And no one
even notices. Everyone just wonders why.

00:38:29.580 --> 00:38:34.100
Because people don’t allow you
to make mistakes. They don’t forgive you.

00:38:34.206 --> 00:38:37.006
But why? I mean, in the end,
who are these people, anyway?

00:38:37.160 --> 00:38:39.394
It might sound a bit silly,
but you have to protect yourself.

00:38:39.540 --> 00:38:42.460
That’s right. -You have to know
how to protect yourself.

00:38:43.005 --> 00:38:45.441
That’s a great state of mind.

00:38:45.655 --> 00:38:51.347
Alright, you approached it all playfully.
Perfect, that’s it. -For me, that’s good.

00:38:51.539 --> 00:38:57.419
But when did you feel, when did you realize,
that you were better than your peers?

00:38:57.658 --> 00:38:59.658
I never thought I was better.

00:39:00.022 --> 00:39:03.222
Wait... your success didn’t
just come out of nowhere.

00:39:03.860 --> 00:39:07.420
You... I actually prepared for this
conversation. -Alright, okay, sorry.

00:39:07.620 --> 00:39:10.980
You won both Topolino and Pinocchio...

00:39:11.220 --> 00:39:17.900
So how can you say you weren’t better?
Not better as a person, but a better skier.

00:39:18.340 --> 00:39:22.020
I mean, in your last year,
your final season of children’s skiing,

00:39:22.260 --> 00:39:27.260
out of 22 races, like your father,
when he scored 24 goals, you won all 22.

00:39:27.860 --> 00:39:30.797
That means you were better.
-But that’s children’s skiing.

00:39:30.953 --> 00:39:33.193
It has nothing to do
with what comes later.

00:39:33.365 --> 00:39:35.565
But those kids go on
to higher levels... -No, no.

00:39:35.968 --> 00:39:39.728
Children’s skiing is very deceptive.

00:39:43.060 --> 00:39:46.940
And there is a difference,
or at least, there used to be.

00:39:47.140 --> 00:39:50.180
I don’t really follow it
that closely anymore,

00:39:50.420 --> 00:39:52.940
so I’m not sure
if it’s still the same today.

00:39:53.180 --> 00:39:56.340
But back when I was a kid, at those races
Topolino, Pinocchio, La Scara

00:39:56.540 --> 00:39:59.860
all those children’s
competitions and categories,

00:40:00.021 --> 00:40:02.848
it turned out that the girls who were
successful in those events

00:40:03.166 --> 00:40:07.060
usually went on to be successful
in adult skiing too.

00:40:07.660 --> 00:40:12.802
While the boys, who were great
at those same races,

00:40:13.130 --> 00:40:18.615
often didn’t do as well later on.
And why such a big difference?

00:40:19.740 --> 00:40:24.099
Because, if you have two
fourteen-year-old boys

00:40:24.356 --> 00:40:27.472
one is already shaving, and the other
doesn’t even know what a razor is.

00:40:27.740 --> 00:40:31.734
That’s just a natural thing
you can’t make up for,

00:40:32.046 --> 00:40:36.757
because the first one
has already grown into a man.

00:40:38.809 --> 00:40:41.969
With girls, that difference
isn’t as noticeable.

00:40:42.420 --> 00:40:48.460
In skiing, at that time, the girls
who were good at those competitions,

00:40:48.700 --> 00:40:52.900
like Tina Maze from Slovenia,
who’s a year younger than me,

00:40:53.100 --> 00:40:56.260
we used to ski together all the time.

00:40:56.500 --> 00:40:59.020
And she was also successful
in those competitions.

00:40:59.260 --> 00:41:02.700
So it turns out that those
who do well in these events

00:41:02.940 --> 00:41:06.845
in women’s skiing, tend to be successful
in adult skiing too, as long as

00:41:08.580 --> 00:41:12.340
they don’t suffer a major injury.
-Well, you develop earlier than we do.

00:41:12.580 --> 00:41:15.420
With us, those adolescent differences
are more noticeable. One is shaving...

00:41:15.660 --> 00:41:19.580
Yes, the differences are bigger.
Some develop earlier, some later.

00:41:19.698 --> 00:41:23.494
And a lot depends on when someone
hits their growth spurt in youth sports.

00:41:23.700 --> 00:41:26.860
Generally, at least in other sports,
and maybe it’s the same in skiing,

00:41:27.013 --> 00:41:29.534
those who "develop late,"
once they catch up,

00:41:29.657 --> 00:41:31.612
often become dominant. -Yes.

00:41:31.959 --> 00:41:36.714
When they get their muscles
and fully grow. So this interests me.

00:41:36.900 --> 00:41:43.220
An athlete’s career is long,
but we all have moments that, at times,

00:41:43.420 --> 00:41:49.540
either launch you forward
and give you confidence,

00:41:49.740 --> 00:41:52.620
which you later use to your advantage...

00:41:52.860 --> 00:41:57.860
Or, in other cases,
they might slow you down...

00:41:59.904 --> 00:42:05.020
Did you have any turning points
in your career?

00:42:06.597 --> 00:42:09.157
No, because I’d remember them.

00:42:09.554 --> 00:42:12.794
So winning Topolino
didn’t really mean to you

00:42:13.260 --> 00:42:17.235
that you were "the one" to go further?
-No. You know what my goal was?

00:42:17.488 --> 00:42:21.808
For example, in Andorra,
there was a competition

00:42:22.055 --> 00:42:24.351
where the winner would get
a Chupa Chups lollipop,

00:42:24.510 --> 00:42:26.230
weighing as much as you weigh.

00:42:26.408 --> 00:42:29.985
They put you on the scale, I’m there,
the Chupa Chups are there, you get it?

00:42:30.145 --> 00:42:33.305
That was amazing to me.
I wasn’t interested in the medal I got.

00:42:33.459 --> 00:42:36.139
I cared about coming home,
back to my school,

00:42:36.362 --> 00:42:39.682
bringing those lollipops,
and all the kids getting to enjoy them.

00:42:40.116 --> 00:42:46.116
That’s what motivated me. Later,
it was also amazing in Levi, Finland,

00:42:46.980 --> 00:42:52.665
where a few years ago they started
giving a reindeer as a prize.

00:42:53.650 --> 00:42:59.180
That didn’t exist when I was skiing.
I find those kinds of things fun.

00:42:59.540 --> 00:43:03.373
And then I told my brother
to compete, but unfortunately

00:43:03.473 --> 00:43:05.482
he came in second, didn’t win.

00:43:05.690 --> 00:43:11.099
So, we didn’t get the reindeer after all.
Those kinds of things motivate me.

00:43:11.792 --> 00:43:16.933
Not everyone is going to say
"Wow, you’re amazing, you were the best."

00:43:18.640 --> 00:43:26.320
Your father didn’t push that either? -No.
I’ve always been my own person. -Bravo.

00:43:29.060 --> 00:43:32.888
Alright, but even though
you’re your own person,

00:43:33.108 --> 00:43:36.841
you grow, and in January 1999,
you take first place,

00:43:36.962 --> 00:43:39.042
that’s your first win
in the combined event, right?

00:43:39.227 --> 00:43:40.747
Yes. In St. Anton.

00:43:41.065 --> 00:43:45.945
And your progress shot upwards quickly.
However, in December of the same year,

00:43:46.380 --> 00:43:55.030
during downhill training, right?
In St. Moritz, there was a fall, a break,

00:43:57.968 --> 00:44:02.437
you fell into the net
and tore four or five ligaments.

00:44:02.615 --> 00:44:04.055
You needed knee reconstruction,

00:44:04.209 --> 00:44:06.491
and the whole process in Selce
took a long time.

00:44:06.700 --> 00:44:08.820
Although the recovery was supposed
to take nine to twelve months,

00:44:09.060 --> 00:44:11.839
you were back on skis
after 52 days, right?

00:44:11.961 --> 00:44:14.105
Do you see that you had some
incredible willpower?

00:44:14.221 --> 00:44:16.341
What does a kid know?
You just take it and do it.

00:44:16.504 --> 00:44:22.144
I didn’t know anything about it.
The people around you were terrified,

00:44:22.500 --> 00:44:30.108
you see their faces and think: "Okay,
I broke my leg, it hurts, but it’s fine.

00:44:30.580 --> 00:44:33.860
Recovery is happening,
you try to lift your leg,

00:44:34.029 --> 00:44:36.452
you lift weights, and so on...

00:44:36.778 --> 00:44:41.100
People make too big a deal
out of absolutely everything in life.

00:44:41.400 --> 00:44:44.800
Of course, it’s not great
that you’re injured,

00:44:45.220 --> 00:44:50.460
but it happened, and you have a goal,
to get back, and that’s it.

00:44:50.597 --> 00:44:53.877
There’s not much mystery
or philosophy in it.

00:44:54.101 --> 00:44:57.341
During the time you can’t ski,
can’t do what you love most,

00:44:57.456 --> 00:45:01.013
you do something else, spend time
with friends, read books, go for walks.

00:45:01.113 --> 00:45:02.959
You do what makes you happy.

00:45:03.124 --> 00:45:05.724
Otherwise, you don’t have time for it,
but now you do.

00:45:05.823 --> 00:45:07.889
And then you make the most of it.

00:45:08.042 --> 00:45:11.741
Because you’ll definitely return to skiing,
and on the third day there will be fog,

00:45:11.905 --> 00:45:15.483
the wind will blow at 100 km/h,
and you’ll wonder:

00:45:17.887 --> 00:45:21.487
"Why did I even come back,
when I was perfectly fine over there?"

00:45:21.687 --> 00:45:23.967
So it’s all just a natural process.

00:45:24.191 --> 00:45:27.991
You just have to accept what comes
your way, whether it’s good or bad.

00:45:28.340 --> 00:45:33.552
Don’t elevate the good too much,
and don’t drag the bad even lower.

00:45:33.664 --> 00:45:35.068
And that’s it.

00:45:35.980 --> 00:45:39.878
It’s the same as when you read a book
about how to stay balanced,

00:45:40.216 --> 00:45:42.656
how to handle this,
how to handle that...

00:45:42.982 --> 00:45:47.183
But it’s not that easy to actually
put it into practice and live that way.

00:45:47.409 --> 00:45:51.289
You have to be practical for yourself.
-Yes, you do, but it’s not easy.

00:45:51.740 --> 00:45:53.553
And you also need to...

00:45:55.062 --> 00:45:59.819
Alright, you’ll put it in perspective,
but the numbers don’t lie.

00:46:00.321 --> 00:46:05.803
It’s an incredible career, marked
by numerous medals and achievements.

00:46:06.810 --> 00:46:09.730
But also surgeries.
You had twelve surgeries, right?

00:46:09.868 --> 00:46:11.588
I had more, but that’s okay...

00:46:11.741 --> 00:46:16.295
Knee, appendix, thyroid...
-It’s tough... -Is that normal?

00:46:16.478 --> 00:46:20.518
Do other female skiers usually have
that many surgeries, or not?

00:46:20.940 --> 00:46:25.100
Some have more, some have fewer.
But everyone has certain issues.

00:46:25.260 --> 00:46:29.620
It’s rare to find a skier, male or female,
who hasn’t been injured.

00:46:29.820 --> 00:46:32.500
For example, Tina Maze from Slovenia.

00:46:32.740 --> 00:46:37.820
She competed in all four disciplines
and actually never had a serious injury.

00:46:38.060 --> 00:46:44.900
She told me, when we spoke:
"Janica, at least you were injured.

00:46:45.100 --> 00:46:47.940
You had time to rest your mind."

00:46:48.300 --> 00:46:52.740
She, season after season,
always had the same rhythm.

00:46:52.980 --> 00:46:57.380
She never had time
to completely step away from it all.

00:46:58.020 --> 00:47:03.700
And people get tired. I thought:
"Yeah, actually, you’re right,

00:47:03.980 --> 00:47:09.420
because no matter how much
you love something,

00:47:09.700 --> 00:47:13.980
when you repeat it every single day,
it becomes monotonous, boring,

00:47:14.260 --> 00:47:18.860
and everything just stretches out.

00:47:19.140 --> 00:47:27.420
But in this case, you get back
that spark for competition,

00:47:27.620 --> 00:47:30.980
that feeling that had faded,
because naturally it would fade.

00:47:31.180 --> 00:47:35.140
It’s hard to maintain constant excitement,
to always be hyped up. -Bravo.

00:47:36.260 --> 00:47:40.900
So, as negative as it may seem,
because there are consequences,

00:47:41.180 --> 00:47:44.980
it hurts, all of that,
you also get that spark back,

00:47:45.260 --> 00:47:48.660
like you’ve never skied before.
That’s great.

00:47:49.300 --> 00:47:54.340
That’s basically what your coach,
doctor, physiotherapist...

00:47:54.580 --> 00:47:58.500
are telling you, to find
something positive in every situation.

00:47:58.740 --> 00:48:02.108
But as an athlete, you’re the one
actually experiencing it,

00:48:02.303 --> 00:48:04.797
and when it happens, it feels terrible.

00:48:04.940 --> 00:48:06.940
And they try to encourage you:
"Now you can read a book,

00:48:07.086 --> 00:48:09.486
we can work on these other parts
of your body..." -Yes, yes.

00:48:09.765 --> 00:48:13.280
And all you really want to say is:
"Okay, just leave me alone..."

00:48:13.500 --> 00:48:18.140
You’re missing that "mindset" of yours,
as they say in Zagreb.

00:48:22.620 --> 00:48:30.500
But we can't deny the three big globes,
seven small ones, three slaloms,

00:48:30.860 --> 00:48:34.100
four combinations...
-Have you learned it all? -Yes.

00:48:35.940 --> 00:48:38.140
Five-time world champion.

00:48:38.380 --> 00:48:41.766
Eight times Croatia’s
Sportswoman of the Year.

00:48:42.062 --> 00:48:49.935
The first skier to be ranked
in world sports as no. 1.

00:48:50.940 --> 00:48:58.500
And six Olympic medals: four gold and
two silver in Salt Lake City and Torino.

00:48:59.380 --> 00:49:09.715
Which races, if we ignore snobs,
chupa chups and medals,

00:49:10.083 --> 00:49:12.911
were really special to you?

00:49:14.425 --> 00:49:15.700
Special?

00:49:16.198 --> 00:49:21.012
A race you’d repeat if you could,
because it wasn’t great?

00:49:21.393 --> 00:49:24.895
I don’t think that way, "what if..."

00:49:26.660 --> 00:49:31.700
That’s wasting time on something
you can’t change.

00:49:32.020 --> 00:49:36.140
You should think about the things
you can change.

00:49:38.100 --> 00:49:43.540
One medal was special to me
and it was in giant slalom,

00:49:43.740 --> 00:49:50.140
at the Olympic Games.
That was the last race.

00:49:53.380 --> 00:49:56.286
I was very exhausted.
Both mentally and physically.

00:49:56.418 --> 00:49:58.888
More mentally than physically.

00:49:59.401 --> 00:50:05.736
At those Olympic Games, I learned
something I didn’t think existed,

00:50:06.200 --> 00:50:09.103
that a person can no longer be happy.

00:50:09.396 --> 00:50:13.056
You know when you have those
great successes of yours?

00:50:13.211 --> 00:50:18.273
You play one match and you’re good,
then another and win a medal,

00:50:18.640 --> 00:50:20.203
then a third medal...

00:50:20.453 --> 00:50:26.281
It’s such an amount of happy emotion
that it’s terribly exhausting.

00:50:27.031 --> 00:50:30.049
It’s impossible to be happy all the time.

00:50:30.316 --> 00:50:33.596
I was emotionally empty.

00:50:33.821 --> 00:50:39.916
If Michael Jackson or Elvis Presley,
who aren’t alive, had walked past me,

00:50:40.220 --> 00:50:42.900
I wouldn’t have looked back.

00:50:43.260 --> 00:50:46.220
I was extremely exhausted.

00:50:47.340 --> 00:50:56.020
I remember coming to a restaurant
before the race to have some tea.

00:50:56.220 --> 00:51:01.180
I was lying on a bench and thought,
"I can’t go on anymore."

00:51:01.700 --> 00:51:06.900
My dad said, "Janička, that’s great!
That’s excellent! It means you’re empty.

00:51:07.140 --> 00:51:11.220
That’s great!" And I thought,
"What is he talking about?"

00:51:11.580 --> 00:51:14.700
I still had two runs left,
and I knew I wouldn’t move

00:51:14.940 --> 00:51:18.020
from that spot until two
or three in the afternoon.

00:51:18.260 --> 00:51:22.500
I just didn’t feel like it.
I was emotionally exhausted.

00:51:22.780 --> 00:51:27.020
I had to check the time to see
when the start was. So I went.

00:51:27.300 --> 00:51:29.300
It was actually kind of funny.

00:51:29.540 --> 00:51:36.140
I got there, and my serviceman,
a Slovenian, Jure Hafner, was there.

00:51:38.140 --> 00:51:41.860
The woman before me went out, but
I wasn’t paying attention to who it was

00:51:42.180 --> 00:51:47.540
or if she had already finished.
I was simply uninterested in life.

00:51:48.420 --> 00:51:53.220
I stood there in front of the starting
gate and someone took off before me.

00:51:53.660 --> 00:51:58.500
I asked Hef what he thought
about me just going back instead.

00:51:58.740 --> 00:52:01.100
I already had three medals,

00:52:01.540 --> 00:52:05.300
and in giant slalom
I wasn’t anything special.

00:52:06.300 --> 00:52:09.380
What would happen if I
just went back, you know?

00:52:09.620 --> 00:52:13.220
He said, "Jana, why are you saying
such nonsense?"

00:52:15.346 --> 00:52:17.626
"Alright," I said, "I have to go!"

00:52:17.802 --> 00:52:21.282
I wasn’t thinking at all about
how the course was set up.

00:52:21.394 --> 00:52:23.394
I was just... empty.

00:52:24.620 --> 00:52:31.540
I put my poles across the timing
device and lowered my head.

00:52:31.653 --> 00:52:33.839
I thought, "I have to go now.

00:52:33.939 --> 00:52:35.899
I can’t turn back,
that would look stupid."

00:52:36.021 --> 00:52:39.861
So I pushed off and skied brilliantly.

00:52:40.740 --> 00:52:45.860
In the end, my dad was right. He said
it was good that I was drained,

00:52:46.140 --> 00:52:51.740
because that way, no emotion
could touch me or stop me.

00:52:51.893 --> 00:52:58.091
I realized that when your mind
is overloaded with thoughts,

00:52:58.224 --> 00:53:00.344
your body stops listening.

00:53:00.940 --> 00:53:04.500
Your body listens best when,
after a million repetitions,

00:53:04.740 --> 00:53:10.100
everything becomes automatic,
like a VHS tape playing on loop.

00:53:10.540 --> 00:53:15.020
It runs on its own and
music plays in your head.

00:53:15.180 --> 00:53:17.900
You don’t have to think about anything.

00:53:18.140 --> 00:53:19.940
That’s a wonderful thing.

00:53:20.220 --> 00:53:23.860
It just takes a lot of repetition
to reach that state.

00:53:24.260 --> 00:53:26.780
But you kept winning all the time?

00:53:27.020 --> 00:53:31.380
Not exactly, actually,
it was every other season.

00:53:31.700 --> 00:53:36.020
One year I was injured,
the next I was skiing again.

00:53:36.260 --> 00:53:38.820
Then another year I had problems
with my thyroid...

00:53:39.060 --> 00:53:41.620
But when you did ski,
you were always at the top.

00:53:41.820 --> 00:53:47.340
Not really. Half of every season
I was stagnating due to injuries.

00:53:52.060 --> 00:53:56.740
That happens even to people
who are the complete opposite of you,

00:53:58.180 --> 00:54:03.100
those who are never satisfied,
no matter how successful they are.

00:54:03.380 --> 00:54:06.740
"It’s not enough, I can do better..."
But where does that lead?

00:54:06.940 --> 00:54:09.420
That’s something you can only
say to yourself.

00:54:09.660 --> 00:54:15.260
I’d come to the course,
and a coach would say,

00:54:15.500 --> 00:54:18.580
"The course is set perfectly for you."

00:54:18.940 --> 00:54:21.540
What does that even mean,
"set perfectly for me"?

00:54:21.780 --> 00:54:24.740
As if some turns suit me
better than others?

00:54:24.940 --> 00:54:29.620
No. There’s no course
that’s made just for me.

00:54:31.100 --> 00:54:33.980
Even when my dad set the course,
it wasn’t "made for me."

00:54:34.220 --> 00:54:36.020
It can’t be.

00:54:36.420 --> 00:54:42.780
That would be too simplistic,
too uncreative to think that way.

00:54:42.870 --> 00:54:46.073
The playing field is never
exactly the same.

00:54:46.192 --> 00:54:47.832
It’s always different.

00:54:48.180 --> 00:54:52.700
Just like Đokovic says,
there’s no such thing as a perfect shot.

00:54:52.940 --> 00:55:00.239
Not a perfect match,
not a perfect shot. Why is that?

00:55:00.489 --> 00:55:04.900
Because it’s like chasing the Holy Grail.

00:55:05.140 --> 00:55:09.460
That’s what keeps you motivated,
to become even better.

00:55:09.940 --> 00:55:12.500
You, clearly, aren’t like that.

00:55:12.740 --> 00:55:16.980
I sometimes think about whether
I could’ve done certain things better.

00:55:18.060 --> 00:55:20.020
Did you ever have a perfect race?

00:55:20.220 --> 00:55:22.660
There’s no such thing as a perfect race.

00:55:22.900 --> 00:55:27.140
Just like there’s no perfect shot.
It’s impossible. Nothing in life is perfect.

00:55:30.060 --> 00:55:39.980
What I loved about slalom,
as a discipline, were the sounds.

00:55:41.300 --> 00:55:44.940
Because when you hit the gates,
they make this specific sound,

00:55:45.140 --> 00:55:48.700
they give you rhythm.

00:55:48.980 --> 00:55:53.391
What amused me was that as I
skied down a particular course,

00:55:53.558 --> 00:55:56.038
I’d listen to what kind of sound
the pole would make,

00:55:56.199 --> 00:55:58.072
if I hit it a little higher
or a little lower.

00:55:58.249 --> 00:56:01.089
What position would my body be in
if I moved my finger like this?

00:56:01.205 --> 00:56:03.882
How would my back react?
How would my legs react?

00:56:03.989 --> 00:56:05.909
Do you do that during training
or in a race?

00:56:06.039 --> 00:56:09.839
During training, not in a race.
In a race, my mind is on other things.

00:56:10.056 --> 00:56:15.219
But in training... that sound,
that’s really cool.

00:56:16.020 --> 00:56:17.700
"Let’s repeat that one!"

00:56:17.900 --> 00:56:20.180
And then you try to repeat it.

00:56:21.740 --> 00:56:27.500
With every tiny movement in your body,
every blink of an eye,

00:56:28.100 --> 00:56:31.300
your body reacts to it all.

00:56:32.020 --> 00:56:36.660
It’s the brain that’s in control.
Your legs don’t move by themselves.

00:56:36.860 --> 00:56:39.900
Everything starts from up here.

00:56:40.100 --> 00:56:43.780
It matters whether your arm
is like this or like that.

00:56:43.940 --> 00:56:50.740
The force won’t transfer the same way
to your skis, or to your legs, back, arms.

00:56:51.100 --> 00:56:53.260
All of that is so important.

00:56:53.900 --> 00:56:57.154
And working on it all the time,
that’s the fun part.

00:56:57.358 --> 00:56:59.865
Fun? -Yes, constant fun.

00:57:00.073 --> 00:57:03.993
It’s not hard, it’s not like
running a marathon.

00:57:04.432 --> 00:57:10.170
It’s never the same,
it’s different, and it’s playful.

00:57:11.020 --> 00:57:16.140
Some people told me that it’s
not quite the same in skiing,

00:57:16.500 --> 00:57:19.340
but it is, just like in most individual
sports, the Olympics are the Olympics.

00:57:19.580 --> 00:57:21.940
Even in skiing? -Yes, in skiing too.

00:57:28.220 --> 00:57:35.449
Ronaldo, Đokovic,
Nadal, Ferrer, Hamilton...

00:57:35.682 --> 00:57:38.206
Who was your biggest rival?
That Swedish skier?

00:57:38.408 --> 00:57:43.805
You mean when I was still competing?
-Yes. -Anja Pärson was my biggest rival.

00:57:44.380 --> 00:57:47.300
Because we both competed
in all four disciplines.

00:57:47.462 --> 00:57:50.022
That doesn’t really exist anymore,
today it’s much more specialized.

00:57:50.198 --> 00:57:53.078
Is there friendship in that,
or mostly rivalry?

00:57:53.254 --> 00:57:56.814
On the course, it’s rivalry.

00:57:57.420 --> 00:58:04.100
I think people often push the idea that
athletes hate each other too much.

00:58:04.300 --> 00:58:07.420
During a race or a match,
you do kind of hate each other,

00:58:07.580 --> 00:58:13.820
it sounds silly, but at the same time,
you respect each other completely.

00:58:14.540 --> 00:58:21.260
You respect that person and you know
exactly what they’ve gone through.

00:58:21.820 --> 00:58:24.500
But I don’t ski against her.

00:58:24.700 --> 00:58:28.598
I ski against everyone,
mostly against myself.

00:58:28.878 --> 00:58:32.972
My motivation was never to beat her.

00:58:34.780 --> 00:58:37.300
Because to beat her, I’d have to beat
everyone else anyway,

00:58:37.509 --> 00:58:40.025
no matter how strong
or weak they were.

00:58:40.540 --> 00:58:45.400
Outside of that, Tina Maze
is the only person

00:58:45.531 --> 00:58:48.853
I still occasionally keep in touch with.

00:58:49.040 --> 00:58:52.619
With social media, it’s easy
to stay connected.

00:58:54.708 --> 00:58:58.087
We’re quite different by nature.

00:58:58.318 --> 00:59:01.306
She’s very passionate,
she shows her emotions openly.

00:59:01.411 --> 00:59:04.790
When she’s upset,
she’ll break a ski pole.

00:59:05.526 --> 00:59:08.366
I, on the other hand, won’t do anything
when I’m unhappy.

00:59:08.732 --> 00:59:12.720
I’ll know that my skiing
wasn’t good that day,

00:59:13.780 --> 00:59:18.420
but I won’t let it frustrate me.
-One last question...

00:59:18.940 --> 00:59:24.660
Do you ever regret not winning
the Snow Queen Trophy?

00:59:24.900 --> 00:59:27.780
I feel sorry, but because of the people.

00:59:28.020 --> 00:59:30.900
Whether I’d won one more
World Cup race or not,

00:59:31.140 --> 00:59:32.980
that didn’t matter much to me.

00:59:33.180 --> 00:59:37.620
What hurt was knowing that people
didn’t get what they truly deserved.

00:59:37.820 --> 00:59:41.460
That’s what felt unfair to me.

00:59:41.700 --> 00:59:44.660
That’s all for this part of our
conversation with Janica Kostelić.

00:59:44.900 --> 00:59:48.740
You’ll be able to watch the second part
in two weeks, on Arena Sport 1.

